[2]
Date: Mon, 5 May 1997 20:48:23 -0300
From: Luiz Jacintho da Silva <luisjs@correionet.com.br>

Caution must be exercised when recommending antibiotics for meningitis,
especially in children. Intravenous penicillin is the drug of choice for the
meningococcus; the pneumococcus however is becoming increasingly resistant
to penicillin and ampicillin as well as other drugs (this resistance is not
beta-lactamase mediated).
This resistance was initially seen in South Africa, Hungary and Spain, but
has already been reported from all continents. Some cities and areas of the
U.S. have high levels of penicillin resistant pneumococcus (PRP). There is
no consensus as to the ideal initial antibiotic choice for pneumococcal
meningitis or bacterial meningitis of undetermined cause in areas where PRP
prevalence is significant. Vancomycin has been a choice with U.S.
pediatricians. Ceftriaxone can be used, at least with relative resistance;
a sensitive strain is one susceptible to less than 0.1 mcg/ml, relative
resistant is a strain resistant to concentrations of 0.1 to 1.0 mcg/ml but
sensitive to more, resistant is a strain resistant to concentrations of 1.0
mcg/ml or more -- as diffusion of ceftriaxone to the central nervous system
(CNS) is much better than for penicillin or ampicillin. This latter drug is
no longer the initial choice in bacterial meningitis.
There is no doubt that this places a considerable burden, financial and
medical, on
the treatment of meningitis, mainly in developing countries. Efficacious
conjugate vaccines for meningococcus and pneumococcus are being developed,
but still are some way off.
Bradley, J. S et al - Consensus: management of infections in children caused
by Streptococcus pneumoniae with decreased susceptibility to penicillin.
Pediatr. Infect. Dis. J. 1995; 14:1037-41
Boken, D. J. et al - Colonization with penicillin-resistant Strepococcus
pneumoniae in a child-care center. Pediatr. Infect. Dis. J. 1995; 14:879-84
American Academy of Pediatrics - Pneumococcal infections. In: Peter G., ed
1994 Red Book: Report of the Committee on Infectious Diseases. 23rd ed Elk
Grove Village, American Academy of Pediatrics; 1994. p.371-375
--
Luiz Jacintho da Silva
